nges of decolonisation, republicanism and radicalism. These studies place dynasties – both European and ‘native’ – at the centre of debate about decolonisation and the form of government of new states, from the sovereigns of Britain, the Netherlands and Japan to the maharajas of India, the sultans of the East Indies and the ‘white rajahs’ of Sarawak. It provides new understanding of the history of decolonisation and of the history of modern monarchy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2020. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAsia.  aSouth Asia.  aSoutheast Asia.  aanti-colonialism.  adecolonisation.  aempire.  aindependence.  amonarchy.  anationalism.  aprincely states.  aroyalty.  asultans.1 aAldrich, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAldrich, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrunero, Donna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoscha, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHampton, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurniadi, Bayu Dardias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasselos, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCreery, Cindy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCreery, Cindy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMilner, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNaik, Priya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStengs, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 